					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Barry Lopez on the Web and Ramona Quimby&#8217;s Portland Street</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 12-19-07</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/barry-lopez_thumb.jpg" align="right" width="201" height="300" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

											<tr>
							<td>&nbsp;</td>
							<td class="image-caption" align="right">Caption: Barry Lopez author photo by Nancy Crampton.</td>
						</tr>
					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>Some authors&#8217; websites share first-person, chatty accounts of their appearances and projects (such as my favorite expansive writer&#8217;s website, <a target="_blank" href="http://mirandajuly.com" title="Miranda July's">Miranda July&#8217;s</a>), and many writers have even launched their own MySpace pages (such as that of <a target="_blank" href="http://www.myspace.com/pamhouston2" title="Pam Houston">Pam Houston</a>), while others are more reserved.
</p>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.barrylopez.com" title="Barry Lopez's website">Barry Lopez&#8217;s website</a> falls into the latter camp.&nbsp; The <a target="_blank" href="http://www.barrylopez.com/index.htm" title="biography">biography</a> refers to him formally as &#8220;Mr. Lopez,&#8221; and you can find notices of his latest publications not under a link labeled &#8220;books&#8221; but instead under the serious-sounding &#8221;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.barrylopez.com/works.htm" title="Work."">Work.&#8221;</a>
</p>
<p>
Only in the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.barrylopez.com/bio.htm" title=""Gallery"">&#8220;Gallery&#8221;</a> section does Lopez let loose, writing about himself ("For most of my writing life I&#8217;ve been driven, like other writers and artists, to explore") and sharing a photo of his very attractive family, his philosophy of writing, and some good advice for aspiring writers:
</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;If I were to offer advice to young writers, it would be this: be discriminating and be discerning about the work you set for yourself. That done, be the untutored traveler, the eager reader, the enthusiastic listener. Put what you learn together carefully and then write thoughtfully, with respect both for the reader and your sources.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>
<a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/writers_listen_to_mountain_lions_in_new_anthology/C39/L39/" title="I like to kid about Barry Lopez">I like to kid about Barry Lopez</a> from time to time, but his website is both informative and dignified, much like his essays and books. I learned that Lopez&#8217;s work has inspired multi-disciplinary art, such <a target="_blank" href="http://www.robineschner.com/" title="Robin Eschner's">Robin Eschner&#8217;s</a> paintings in response to his writings, and the liner-note short story Lopez wrote for cellist David Darling&#8217;s &#8220;Dark Wood.&#8221;  He&#8217;ll be editing two special issues of the University of Hawaii-based literary journal <a target="_blank" href="http://www.hawaii.edu/mjournal/" title="Manoa">Manoa</a>, and his recent book <a target="_blank" href="http://www.homegroundproject.com/" title="Home Ground">Home Ground</a> has given rise to a <a target="_blank" href="http://www.barrylopez.com/disc.htm" title="forthcoming landscape photography exhibit">forthcoming landscape photography exhibit</a> at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art.
</p>
<p>
Barry Lopez&#8217;s website feels like a little buoy of calm and poise on the Internet, bobbing peacefully amid the goo of too much self-revelation and too little reflection.
</p>
<p>
Speaking of notable Oregon personages, Beverly Cleary&#8217;s Ramona Quimby is one of my favorite fictional characters, and Denise Hamilton recently wrote <a target="_blank" href="http://www.latimes.com/features/books/la-bk-hamilton9dec09,0,384216.story?coll=la-home-middleright" title="an essay for the Los Angeles Times">an essay for the Los Angeles Times</a> about stumbling across Klickitat Street in the Portland suburbs, the street where the Quimbys lived.&nbsp; Hamilton writes: &#8220; Born in 1916 on a farm in Yamhill, Ore., Beverly Bunn moved to Portland as a child. Although she lived several blocks away, on 37th Street, she&#8217;d always liked the name Klickitat Street.&#8221; (<a target="_blank" href="http://maudnewton.com/blog/?p=8232" title="Via Maud Newton">Via Maud Newton</a>.) 
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
